<p>=20
A <b>township</b> in some states of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/United_States" title=3D"United States">United States</a> is a small g=
eographic area.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(United_States)#cite_note-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The term is used in four ways.
</p>
<ol><li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Survey_township" title=
=3D"Survey township">survey township</a> is a geographic reference used to =
define property location for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deed"=
 title=3D"Deed">deeds</a> and grants as surveyed and platted by the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_General_Land_Office" title=
=3D"United States General Land Office">United States General Land Office</a=
> (GLO). A survey township is nominally six by six miles square, or 23,040 =
acres (93.200 km<sup>2</sup>).</li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_township" title=3D"Civ=
il township">civil township</a> is a unit of local government, generally a =
civil division of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/County_(United=
_States)" title=3D"County (United States)">county</a>. Counties are the pri=
mary divisional entities in many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
.S._states" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"U.S. states">states</a>, thus th=
e powers and organization of townships varies from state to state. Civil to=
wnships are generally given a name, sometimes written with the included abb=
reviation "Twp".</li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charter_township" title=3D"C=
harter township">charter township</a>, found only in the state of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michigan" title=3D"Michigan">Michigan</a>=
, is similar to a civil township. Provided certain conditions are met, a ch=
arter township is mostly exempt from annexation to contiguous cities or vil=
lages, and carries additional rights and responsibilities of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_rule" title=3D"Home rule">home rule</a>.</l=
i>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judiciary_of_Nevada" title=
=3D"Judiciary of Nevada">justice township</a>, found only in the state of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nevada" title=3D"Nevada">Nevada</a>=
, is not a government.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(United_States)#cite_note-2"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Townships in Nevada correspond only to justice courts, which handle lo=
w-level, low-value lawsuits and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mi=
sdemeanor" title=3D"Misdemeanor">misdemeanors</a> with some court functions=
 carried out by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constables_in_the_=
United_States" title=3D"Constables in the United States">constables</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Township_(United_States)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Townships can only c=
ontain one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cities_in_Nevad=
a" title=3D"List of cities in Nevada">incorporated city</a> with geographic=
 areas larger than the city's boundaries to include <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Unincorporated_towns_in_Nevada" title=3D"Unincorporated t=
owns in Nevada">unincorporated land</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(United_States)#c=
ite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup></li></ol>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Survey_townships">Survey to=
wnships</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTown=
ship_(United_States)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Survey townships"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Survey_township" title=3D"Survey=
 township">Survey township</a></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Theoreticaltownshipmap.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"h=
ttps://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Theoreticaltownshi=
pmap.gif/250px-Theoreticaltownshipmap.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200"=
 height=3D"216" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"694" data-file=
-height=3D"751"></a><figcaption>Diagram of survey township</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Systemic_numbering_in_the_Public_Land_Survey_System.svg" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/=
thumb/3/35/Systemic_numbering_in_the_Public_Land_Survey_System.svg/500px-Sy=
stemic_numbering_in_the_Public_Land_Survey_System.svg.png" decoding=3D"asyn=
c" width=3D"400" height=3D"279" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"386" data-file-height=3D"269"></a><figcaption>Hierarchy of systemic num=
bering in the PLSS</figcaption></figure>
<p>Survey townships are generally referred to by a number based on the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Survey_System" title=3D"Pu=
blic Land Survey System">Public Land Survey System</a> (PLSS). A reference =
to the township will look something like "Township 2 North Range 3 East", o=
r "T2N,R3E" and such a notation is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Public_Land_Survey_System#Understanding_property_descriptions" tit=
le=3D"Public Land Survey System">property descriptions based on the PLSS</a=
>. Townships were originally surveyed and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Plat" title=3D"Plat">platted</a> by the United States General Land =
Office, using contracted private survey crews, and are marked on the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Geological_Survey" title=
=3D"United States Geological Survey">United States Geological Survey</a> ma=
ps of the United States.
</p><p>Townships are normally a square approximately six miles (9.7&nbsp;km=
) on a side with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_directio=
n" title=3D"Cardinal direction">cardinal</a> boundaries conforming to merid=
ians and parallels, containing 36 sections of one square mile (2.6&nbsp;km<=
sup>2</sup>) each. The northern and westernmost tier of sections in each to=
wnship are designed to take up the convergence of the east and west townshi=
p boundary lines or range lines, as well as any error in the survey measure=
ments, and therefore these sections vary slightly from being one square mil=
e or 640 acres (260&nbsp;ha). Survey townships exist in some form in most s=
tates other than the original <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thir=
teen_Colonies" title=3D"Thirteen Colonies">Thirteen Colonies</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kentucky" title=3D"Kentucky">Kentucky</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tennessee" title=3D"Tennessee">T=
ennessee</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vermont" title=3D"Ve=
rmont">Vermont</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine" tit=
le=3D"Maine">Maine</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"whit=
e-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Acc=
uracy_dispute#Disputed_statement" title=3D"Wikipedia:Accuracy dispute"><spa=
n title=3D"The material near this tag is possibly inaccurate or nonfactual.=
 (August 2011)">dubious</span></a> =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Talk:Township_(United_States)#Dubious" title=3D"Talk:Township (U=
nited States)">discuss</a></i>]</sup> Irregular or fractional townships wit=
h fewer than a full 36&nbsp;sections are created where full townships canno=
t be laid out due to existing senior boundaries, such as Spanish/Mexican <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranchos_of_California" title=3D"Ranc=
hos of California">ranchos</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
dian_reservation" title=3D"Indian reservation">Indian reservations</a>, sta=
te boundary lines, etc.
</p><p>In Kentucky, the Jackson Purchase (the area west of the Tennessee Ri=
ver) is divided into townships and ranges. In Tennessee, the entire state i=
s surveyed into townships and ranges that make up 13 survey districts of th=
e Tennessee State Survey. In extreme northern Maine there is an area divide=
d into townships and ranges oriented to true north. A region in the central=
 part of the state, made up of 17 surveys, is divided into townships, but t=
hese are not oriented to true north.  The remainder of the state is on <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metes_and_bounds" title=3D"Metes and b=
ounds">metes and bounds</a>. Similarly, Vermont and New Hampshire are mostl=
y metes-and-bounds states, but have areas in the north that are surveyed in=
to townships not oriented to true north. Most of Ohio is surveyed using the=
 Public Land Survey System, but several sizable areas are metes-and-bounds,=
 including the Virginia Military Reserve, Donation Tract, French Grant and =
the three Moravian grants (Gnadenhutten, Schoenbrunn and Salem).  A 150,000=
-acre (61,000&nbsp;ha) area in southern Indiana (<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Clark%27s_Grant" title=3D"Clark's Grant">Clark's Grant</a>) =
is not surveyed into townships, but is still a gridded survey.  Portions of=
 the Texas State Survey use square townships. Sizeable portions of Alaska, =
Arizona, California, Idaho, Montana, Oregon and Washington, are unsurveyed.=
 Substantial swampy areas in Florida and Louisiana are also unsurveyed.
</p><p>Both New York and Pennsylvania have metes-and-bounds surveys, but in=
 the western parts of these states, the metes-and-bounds form square townsh=
ips many of which are also civil townships.  Besides these, nearly every st=
ate has areas of metes-and-bounds that were never included in the grids (li=
ke along major rivers) or were removed from the grid, usually due to survey=
ing mistakes.
</p>
