<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_township" titl=
e=3D"Civil township">Civil township</a></div>
<p>The township government is a unit of local government, often rural. Town=
ships are geographic and political subdivisions of a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/County_(United_States)" title=3D"County (United States)"=
>county</a>. The township is identified by a name, such as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penn_Township,_Cumberland_County,_Pennsylvania" ti=
tle=3D"Penn Township, Cumberland County, Pennsylvania">Penn Township, Cumbe=
rland County, Pennsylvania</a>. The responsibilities and the form of the to=
wnship government is specified by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/State_legislature_(United_States)" title=3D"State legislature (United S=
tates)">state legislature</a>.
</p><p>The most common form of township government has an elected board of =
trustees or supervisors. Some additional offices, such as clerk or <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constable#United_States" title=3D"Constab=
le">constable</a>, may also be elected. The most common governmental respon=
sibilities of townships include oversight of such things as road maintenanc=
e, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land-use_planning" title=3D"Lan=
d-use planning">land-use planning</a>, and trash collection. Many townships=
 in Ohio, Michigan, New Jersey and Pennsylvania provide police and fire pro=
tection, similar to what an incorporated city would provide.
</p><p>In most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midwest" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Midwest">midwestern states</a>, a civil township often=
 corresponds to a single survey township, although in less populated areas,=
 the civil township may be made up of all or portions of several survey tow=
nships. In areas where there are natural features such as a lake or river, =
the civil township boundaries may follow the geographic features rather tha=
n the survey township boundaries. Municipalities such as cities may incorpo=
rate or annex land in a township, which is then generally removed from town=
ship government. Only one state, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
ndiana" title=3D"Indiana">Indiana</a>, has township governments covering al=
l its area and population.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(United_States)#cite_note-5"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In other states, some types of municipalities, like villages, rema=
in a part of the township while cities are not. As <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Urban_area" title=3D"Urban area">urban areas</a> expand, a=
 civil township may entirely disappear=E2=80=94see, for example, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mill_Creek_Township,_Hamilton_County,_Ohio" =
title=3D"Mill Creek Township, Hamilton County, Ohio">Mill Creek Township, H=
amilton County, Ohio</a>. In other expanding urban areas, the township may =
incorporate itself into a city; this can be seen in the numerous square cit=
ies of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hennepin_County,_Minnesota"=
 title=3D"Hennepin County, Minnesota">Hennepin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Anoka_County,_Minnesota" title=3D"Anoka County, Minnesota=
">Anoka</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_County=
,_Minnesota" title=3D"Washington County, Minnesota">Washington</a> counties=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minnesota" title=3D"Minnesota"=
>Minnesota</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montgomery_Cou=
nty,_Ohio" title=3D"Montgomery County, Ohio">Montgomery County, Ohio</a>, c=
ities of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trotwood,_Ohio" title=3D"=
Trotwood, Ohio">Trotwood</a> (1996, formerly Madison Township), <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huber_Heights,_Ohio" title=3D"Huber Heights, =
Ohio">Huber Heights</a> (1980, Wayne Township), and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Kettering,_Ohio" title=3D"Kettering, Ohio">Kettering</a> =
(1955, Van Buren Township) are further examples of townships incorporating =
into cities.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(Pennsylvania)" ti=
tle=3D"Township (Pennsylvania)">Pennsylvania</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Jersey" title=3D"New Jersey">New Jersey</a> have civ=
il townships that are not based on the PLSS survey system, but on the older=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metes_and_bounds" title=3D"Metes =
and bounds">metes and bounds</a> survey system. A <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Township_(New_Jersey)" title=3D"Township (New Jersey)">New =
Jersey township</a> differs only in name from other municipalities: its bou=
ndaries are fixed, it is an incorporated body, and it is free to adopt anot=
her form of government. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federa=
l_government_of_the_United_States" title=3D"Federal government of the Unite=
d States">federal government</a> formerly had a revenue sharing arrangement=
 that separately allocated funding for townships and other <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_civil_division" title=3D"Minor civil divisio=
n">minor civil division</a> types such as cities or boroughs;<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Towns=
hip_(United_States)#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> some New Jersey municipalities,=
 such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verona,_New_Jersey" t=
itle=3D"Verona, New Jersey">Township of the Borough of Verona</a> or <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Orange,_New_Jersey" title=3D"South=
 Orange, New Jersey">Township of South Orange Village</a>, changed their na=
mes to qualify for additional federal aid at the expense of municipalities =
of other types.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Charter_townships">Charter =
townships</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTo=
wnship_(United_States)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Charter townships"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charter_township" ti=
tle=3D"Charter township">Charter township</a></div>
<p>Michigan has created <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charter_to=
wnship" title=3D"Charter township">charter townships</a> as a separate type=
 of government to allow greater flexibility for township governments to ser=
ve urbanized populations. In Michigan, as in other states with like systems=
 (though sometimes different names), a township is an administrative divisi=
on of a county, which is an administrative division of the state. Counties =
and townships are local organs through which state law and public policy ar=
e administered, adapted to local need to the extent the law allows. A chart=
er township is a township that has been granted a charter, which allows it =
certain rights and responsibilities of home rule that are generally interme=
diary in scope between those of a city (a semi-autonomous jurisdiction in M=
ichigan) and a village, which (unless it is a home-rule village) is subject=
 to the authority of the township(s) in which it is located.
</p><p>Charter townships may also reorganize themselves into municipalities=
, as can be seen in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wayne_County,_=
Michigan" title=3D"Wayne County, Michigan">Wayne County, Michigan</a>, and =
elsewhere in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detroit_metropoli=
tan_area" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Detroit metropolitan area">Detroit=
 metropolitan area</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Census_statistics">Census s=
tatistics</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTo=
wnship_(United_States)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Census statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Towns and townships are sometimes considered <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Minor_civil_division" title=3D"Minor civil division">minor ci=
vil divisions</a> of counties by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/United_States_Census_Bureau" title=3D"United States Census Bureau">Unite=
d States Census Bureau</a> for statistical purposes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Township_(Unit=
ed_States)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to the Census Bureau, in 200=
2, town or township government applied to 16,504 organized governments in t=
he following 20 states:
</p>
